25:<Technically, you could compute all the inferred dependencies right at the beginning, and actually that's how I first did it. But I found it kind of confusing, since there are so many rules you could apply to every FD; e.g. you could apply some augmentation rule to one FD and then combine the result with another FD and apply the transitive rule and then... and then... how do you even know whether there are still more rules to be inferred? You might have already found them all and you don't even know it! Also, you might end up with a bunch of inferred FDs that you won't even need later on in the decomposition. Personally, I find it more convenient to calculate the closure of the left-hand side of all FDs and then just take it from there. But honestly, I have no idea if this is the best way to do it (probably not), but I haven't really found a good algorithm so far to compute the set of all inferred dependencies :( but if you happen to come across one, please let me know! ;)>
