30:<Hmm. Try to look at it this way. In order to prove that an FD holds, you need to show that all tuples that agree on a certain attribute (the one on the left-hand side of the FD) also agree on some other attribute (the one on the right-hand side of the FD). MVDs, however, only state that if two tuples agree on a certain attribute, then there has to be a third tuple that satisfies certain condition. At no point does the MVD try to enforce some sort of equality that involves the first two tuples (which would be needed to establish an FD).

I know this sounds pretty wishy washy. I've been trying to come up with a formal proof that shows that MVDs cannot ever have any impact of FDs, but I haven't succeeded so far :(>
